    "summary": "Checkpoint Charlie was the most famous crossing point between East and West Berlin during the [[event:113|Cold War]], located at the junction of Friedrichstrasse and Zimmerstrasse. The checkpoint was operational from 1961, shortly after the [[event:2713|Berlin Wall's construction]], and was designated specifically for foreign nationals, diplomats, and military personnel of the Western powers — ordinary East and West German civilians used different crossing points. Its name derived from the third letter of the NATO phonetic alphabet.\n\nThe site became one of the most potent Cold War symbols and the setting for several dramatic confrontations and espionage incidents. In October 1961, American and Soviet tanks faced each other for sixteen hours in the single most dangerous direct military standoff of the Berlin crisis. The checkpoint was used for numerous prisoner exchanges and spy swaps between the superpowers. Numerous East Germans attempted to escape across or through the Wall near Checkpoint Charlie, with some succeeding through creative methods and others dying in the attempt. After the [[event:2681|fall of the Berlin Wall]] in 1989, the checkpoint was formally dismantled in June 1990. It is now a major tourist attraction in unified Berlin, with a museum dedicated to escape attempts from East Germany.",
